<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<title>Le Chevalier de Saint-George, Afro-French Composer, Violinist & Conductor</title>
<meta name="description" content="Joseph de Bologne, the Chevalier de Saint-George (also called Joseph Boulogne, the Chevalier de Saint-Georges) was an Afro-French composer, violinist and conductor who was born in the French colony of Guadeloupe on December 25, 1745. First known as an athlete and France's finest fencer, Saint-George quickly developed an impressive musical reputation as a composer, violinist and conductor of two of France's finest orchestras. He played music with Queen Marie-Antoniette regularly, but joined the French Revolution and soon became Colonel of 1,000 volunteers of color. He served heroically but was imprisoned for political reasons. Upon release he traveled to Haiti, then returned to conduct his final orchestra, the Circle of Harmony. Saint-George died in Paris on June 10, 1799. His life and music were ignored for nearly two centuries until their rediscovery by musicians and historians in the  late 20th century. A DVD of his life is &quot;Le Mozart Noir&quot;, based on a television documentary seen on television in many countries.">
<meta name="keywords" content="Joseph de Bologne, Afro-French composer, Afro-French violinist, colonel, Fencing champion, France's best fencer, Afro-French conductor, Guadeloupe">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 6.0">
<meta name="ProgId" content="FrontPage.Editor.Document">
<meta name="Microsoft Theme" content="none">
<meta name="Microsoft Border" content="none, default">
</head>

